The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source;

GlobalFoundries is strongly committed to preventing environmental, health, and safety incidents. This commitment is inherent to a comprehensive Risk Management Program in place that covers areas such as design, installation, operating procedures, maintenance, and employee training associated with the covered process units at our facility. It is our policy to implement appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of regulated substances. Unforeseeably, if such a release does occur, we have highly trained emergency response personnel to control and mitigate the effects of a chemical release.

The stationary source and regulated substances handled;

The Malta facility has two covered chemicals under the Risk Management Program. The two chemicals are anhydrous ammonia (threshold quantity of 10,000 pounds) and ammonia in an aqueous solution greater than 20% (threshold quantity of 20,000 pounds). A brief overview of each substance is below. 
1.	Anhydrous Ammonia System – the anhydrous ammonia system consists of the truck unloading station, a storage tank, two vaporizers, a purification unit, two NH4OH generation units, and associated piping / instrumentation. The maximum intended inventory for the anhydrous ammonia system is 76,500 pounds. Based on the worst-case release scenario, the toxic distance to endpoint would be 3.2 miles from the point source. Due to offsite receptors, the anhydrous ammonia system is the only Program Level 3 process at the Malta facility. 
